proof.p:
Write \basisfont{B} = \{ \uvec{u}_1, \uvec{u}_2, \dotsc, \uvec{u}_n \}, and suppose \uvec{v} and \uvec{w} are vectors in V. Then each of \uvec{v} and \uvec{w} have a unique expression as a linear combination of the vectors in \basisfont{B} (). So we can write
\uvec{v} \amp = a_1 \uvec{u}_1 + a_2 \uvec{u}_2 + \dotsb + a_n \uvec{u}_n \text{,} \uvec{w} \amp = b_1 \uvec{u}_1 + b_2 \uvec{u}_2 + \dotsb + b_n \uvec{u}_n \text{,}
for some unique collections of scalars a_1,a_2,\dotsc,a_n and b_1,b_2,\dotsc,b_n. These linear combinations tell us the coordinate vectors of \uvec{v} and \uvec{w}:
\rmatrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} \amp = (a_1,a_2,\dotsc,a_n) \text{,} \rmatrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B} \amp = (b_1,b_2,\dotsc,b_n) \text{.}
We add linear combinations by collecting like terms, so we have \uvec{v} + \uvec{w} = (a_1 + b_1) \uvec{u}_1 + (a_2 + b_2) \uvec{u}_2 + \dotsb + (a_n + b_n) \uvec{u}_n . The coordinate vector of this sum is then
\rmatrixOf{\uvec{v} + \uvec{w}}{B} \amp = (a_1 + b_1, a_2 + b_2, \dotsc, a_n + b_n) \amp = (a_1, a_2, \dotsc, a_n) + (b_1, b_2, \dotsc, b_n) \amp = \rmatrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} + \rmatrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B} , as desired.
We scalar multiply a linear combination by distributing the scalar across the vector additions, so for every scalar k we have k \uvec{v} = k a_1 \uvec{u}_1 + k a_2 \uvec{u}_2 + \dotsb + k a_n \uvec{u}_n . The coordinate vector of this scalar multiple is then
\rmatrixOf{k \uvec{v}}{B} \amp = (k a_1, k a_2, \dotsc, k a_n) \amp = k (a_1, a_2, \dotsc, a_n) \amp = k \rmatrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} , as desired.
This statement is just the combination of the first two.

li.p:

says that  \ucobmtrx{B}{B''}  is the one unique matrix so that
 \ucobmtrx{B}{B''} \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} = \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B''} 
holds for every vector \uvec{v} in V.

Set  P = \ucobmtrx{B'}{B''} \ucobmtrx{B}{B'} .
Then for every vector \uvec{v} in V we have

	 P \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} \amp = (\ucobmtrx{B'}{B''} \ucobmtrx{B}{B'}) \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} 
	 \amp = \ucobmtrx{B'}{B''} (\ucobmtrx{B}{B'} \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B}) 
	 \amp = \ucobmtrx{B'}{B''} \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B'} 
	 \amp = \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B''} 
.
So P also satisfies
 P \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} = \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B''} 
for every vector \uvec{v} in V.
The uniqueness of  \ucobmtrx{B}{B''}  then tells us that P = \ucobmtrx{B}{B''},
or  \ucobmtrx{B'}{B''} \ucobmtrx{B}{B'} = \ucobmtrx{B}{B''}  as desired.
